---
OVERLOADING IN C++

This C++ code illustrates the overloading of
a function.  There are two different max()
functions being used, even though the name
"max" is the same for each of them.

This C++ code also illustrates how a program
can be written in more than one file. Note that
the header file find_max.h gets included at the
top of each of the .c files.

To compile this program, you can give
the command

   CC *.c

If you have the GNU C/C++ compiler,
then you can give the command

   make

to compile this program.

---
Have you noticed that some of our C++ programs
do not have the line

   return 0;

at the end of main()?  Recently, the ANSI C++
committee made the inclusion of that line
optional.  If the line is missing, then the
value 0 gets returned to the operating
system by default.
